{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: Yes, and I found that most interesting, because he did not really go out of his way to help Hoover do anything between the time of the election and the time of his inauguration. To the contrary, he sort of stood back and let it happen.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes, and the bitterness got very great between them. Hoover wanted him to join with him, issue some proclamations, to close the banks and do other kind of things. Roosevelt felt, I`m not president yet, why should I have responsibility for this without authority? And actually, I think he was right about that, because Hoover said to a friend privately, that if Roosevelt had agreed to join him, he would be repudiating the New Deal.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 But it is true that Roosevelt let the economy sink lower and lower and lower, so we got to a point where there was no economic pulse at all. We were on a barter economy. Even before he closed the banks, four-fifth of the banks were closed. So can you imagine, Bob, if you had put your money in one of the 10,000 banks that had gone out of business? And you would be done. You know, it was over for people. And they really wondered, how were they going to live?}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 So in the inaugural when he famously said, "the only thing we have to fear is fear itself," that was inspired nonsense. People had real things to fear about how they were going to put food on the table. But through this kind of conjuring act, a theatrical act, he was able to restore people`s hope and faith, even though the Depression didn`t end for another seven years.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
