\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Well, you know, there`s a lot of dispute as to whether }{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ul\cf2 Raymond Moley}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 , his aide, wrote it or not. And I end up sorting through all the various accounts, and I conclude that Roosevelt actually wrote most of it himself. He liked to think that he was a good writer, and he had written, you know, some articles in the `20s. He wrote a screenplay. He was a failed screenwriter.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: Really?}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: He wrote a screenplay about John Paul Jones when he had polio in Warm Springs, and was looking -- was out of politics looking for something to do. So he kind of fancied himself a writer.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 The more -- to my mind, the more astonishing speech, the one that really transformed communications forever was the first fireside chat, which took place eight days later, on March 12th, 1933, eight days after he was sworn in. And this completely revolutionized communications in the United States -- and in the world, really.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: You know, I have always thought, or it has occurred to me that the greatest and most effective leaders were those who understood the media in which most people got their news. The founders were great writers, and the written word was how people got most of their news. Jack Kennedy, obviously, was the first person to recognize the power of television. But FDR figured out radio.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yeah.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: And because he did, it seems to me that a great deal of his success could be attributed to that. He was the first person on the radio who talked as if we -- you and I are talking. Always before that, it was this -- if someone -- the politician was talking to a large crowd, 200 or 300 people or 1,000 people.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Exactly.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: He figured out that you talk one on one, and that made him so effective.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0
\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 When Roosevelt did those fireside chats, who wrote those speeches? Did he write those? Did he have help on them? And what was it that caused him to recognize how this medium worked?}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Well, there are, again, there are a lot of different accounts of how that first one was written, and Roosevelt later said that he looked out at a workman taking down the scaffolding from his inauguration and said, "I want to write a speech about banking that he can understand." And some of his aides said, yeah, he really did do a lot of it. Others say it was a Hoover treasury official, Arthur Ballentine, who wrote most of that first fireside chat.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 But the first two words to my mind were definitely Roosevelt`s, and they are, "my friends." And that`s a revolutionary idea for the reasons you describe. Instead of shouting at people, as leaders for thousands of years had.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: The voice of God kind of approach, as someone has recently said.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260
\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes, voice of God, exactly. So he was conversing -- and I would read all these letters in the Roosevelt library that said, "I felt like you were sitting in my living room with me." They -- it was almost magic. And the same people who had been engaged in these terrifying bank runs, elbowing each other out the way to take their money out of the bank the last -- the week before, lined up the next day to start to put their money patriotically back into the bank, after listening to Roosevelt.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 So that`s leadership. If you can get people to take money from under the mattress, which he explicitly asked them to do, and put it back in the bank -- but he realized it wasn`t enough, and when he got back from giving that speech, he said, it`s time for some liquid refreshment, and he speeded passage of the repeal of Prohibition through Congress, because he knew there were other things he had to do to raise people`s spirits.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: You know, another wonderful thing about your book is, I went back and read -- I had never read that first fireside chat. I heard about it, I knew about it, I remember the part where he started out, "my friends." But when you break it down, he really did explain some very complex issues, I mean, credit, the interest rates and all of that, how banks work -- which I suspect not many people knew very much about that at the time. But it`s a remarkable explanation amongst other things.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: He was really a teacher. And he held two press conferences a week -- can you imagine? Nine hundred and ninety-eight press conferences. And they were also efforts to be the explainer in chief. He would explain what they were trying to do.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 So when things would not go well, at least he would be out there trying to explain why and trying to fix it.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0
\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 See, this is the big difference between Franklin Roosevelt and George W. Bush, to my mind, is that right now, the economy is strong, but Americans think that we`re on the wrong track. In 1933, we had 80 percent unemployment in some areas, with no end in sight, and yet people thought we were on the right track, and they overwhelmingly reelected Roosevelt.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 Why? Because they got the sense from him that every day he was getting up -- even if he would spend most of the day in bed, which he sometimes did -- but he was working the problem. And he had Eleanor out riding coach class -- can you imagine the first lady riding coach -- telling him what was working and not working in the New Deal so he could make those midcourse corrections. And that brought his competence level up, where people felt, well, you know, he`s trying. That phrase from the campaign, "bold, persistent experimentation." Try one thing. If it doesn`t work, admit it frankly. Try something else. But above all, try something.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 That is what the New Deal was about. It wasn`t a plan. It wasn`t all good. There were some really dumb things that they did. I mean, they regulated literally -- regulation was so out of control, they regulated the burlesque industry about how many times a stripper could take off her clothes at night. A Washington bureaucrat was determining that. So they had some silly ideas that were part of the New Deal, but they also planted 3 billion trees in the Civilian Conservation Corps. The bridges and tunnels that you go through, very good chance they were built in this period.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 He always was making forward progress against the Depression, so even though the Depression didn`t end, people thought he was working the problem. And that, I think, is at the root of President Bush`s problems right now, that people don`t get the sense that he`s out there fighting for them every day.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: Why did he have such a good hold on what the public would accept and what they would take? I remember hearing Doris Kearns Goodwin - - I have never forgotten what she said about him -- she said, he was always just a little bit ahead of the polls. He had this tremendous ability to sense what the system would tolerate, is another way to put it.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes. He was very long-headed, is the way some people describe him. He didn`t have a clear plan. It was very instinctive. }{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ul\cf2 Raymond Moley}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 , his aide, said that to say that the New Deal was a plan was like saying that a boy`s bedroom with dirty clothes and broken baseball bats had been put there by an interior decorator. You know, they were improvising, but he understood how far he could go.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And I have a chapter on Social Security in 1935, and it was a very close thing. It almost didn`t get enacted. He knew exactly -- you know, he disappointed a lot of liberals by not pushing further -- he knew exactly how much the system could tolerate.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 I think there are some similarities to Bill Clinton in terms of his political skills. So I kind of saw him as almost a cross between Reagan and Clinton. And Reagan adored him, even though he didn`t agree with a lot of his policies. He made sure that that memorial was built on the Mall in Washington, and he learned a tremendous amount from Roosevelt about the theater of the presidency, that you had to play a role.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: Did he change -- I mean, we said at the beginning of this that if people thought of him as a real lightweight before he came to the presidency. Had he changed in ways that we just didn`t understand? Or did he remain about the same, and he just was able to demonstrate how smart he really was once he was in a position where he could exercise that power?}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: I think he changed. He never was an intellectual. I mean, Herbert Hoover was much, much more intelligent than he was, but I think he deepened his understanding of Washington when he was assistant secretary of the Navy under Woodrow Wilson. He understood how to get things done in government, the gearing of government, which is really important. Because just passing laws is not enough. You have to make it happen. So he learned that as a bureaucrat.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And then 39 years old, stricken with polio, and that experience at Warm Springs was absolutely critical. Because he understood that people were stricken by fate, like him, that it was beyond their control, and that it was up to us collectively as a society to protect people from what he called the winds of chance and the hurricanes of disaster.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: What could today`s modern politicians learn from Roosevelt? I think one thing you have just stressed is staying in touch, because my observation, after being in Washington for more than three decades, is that when you come right down to it, the White House is the easiest place -- maybe in the entire country -- to become disconnected from reality. Nobody comes in there unless it`s by the president`s invitation. People have a hard time ever telling the president what they really mean. And you`re cut off, you have the whole federal government at your disposal. I think it`s very easy for any president to almost cut himself off from reality. But you`re saying that Roosevelt found a way to stay connected with reality.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes, and I think he felt it especially necessary since he wasn`t mobile, since he couldn`t go around and look himself. And this is where Eleanor and her friend Lorena Hickok, who was a brilliant newspaper woman, they were so critical, because they became his eyes and ears and they traveled around the country to figure out what wasn`t working.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And he wanted to hear the bad news. If you`re president and you don`t want to hear the bad news, you`re going to be in trouble. And you have to make these midcourse corrections. This is something that we`re learning today.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And I also think that most of the time, not always -- when it came to the Holocaust, he kept one loyalist around too long -- but most the time, he put performance ahead of loyalty, not loyalty ahead of performance. If you weren`t performing, he would freeze you out. He would layer you. He wouldn`t can you to your face, but he would figure out how to basically strip you of your duties. He would assign somebody else the same job without telling you.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 He wanted the best. And he was -- if you briefed him in the morning, he would always have two aides come in with breakfast in bed and they`d stand there in his bedroom, they would tell him what was going on -- if you didn`t give him early warning on what was coming down the pike politically, you were not in that job for very long. And he hated surprises. And he was an unbelievable -- he had been a reporter in college, but he was an unbelievable vacuum cleaner of information. And it wasn`t just -- he had tremendous intellectual curiosity, even though he didn`t have a high intellect.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: But he also had this tremendous ability to read people, it seems to me.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj
\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0
\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: No matter what they said to him.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes.}{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: And it seems to me that is something that`s crucial for every president, because people are always awed by the office. It`s very difficult for them to tell the president exactly what`s on their mind, but Roosevelt seemed to see beyond that. He could see, I know what this guy is saying to me, it seemed to me he would say, and I think maybe that was his greatest talent.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: And sometimes he would filibuster in the meeting -- Reagan style, tell a long story about buried treasure on Campobello or whatever, and the guy would leave and realize, whether if it was Huey Long or anybody else, that he hadn`t told him anything and they hadn`t gotten what they wanted. So he was very skillful about sort of manipulating people -- even Eleanor said, I was just one who served his purposes. And in that sense, the great confidence and the wonderful temperament in some ways was a shield. He did not have close friends, and there was a coldness to him below the good spirits.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
