\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 BOB SCHIEFFER: It -- and I think you -- you underline this in your book, in many ways that he also self-sacrificed in asking people -- he wasn`t afraid to ask people to sacrifice. So much of the time today, it seems to me, our modern leaders are afraid to ask people for real sacrifice, for fear it will undercut their support. He told people, this is going to be tough, and here`s what we`re all going to have to do.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 JONATHAN ALTER: Yes. And in that sense, he`s very much in the tradition of American presidents, and I would argue that President Bush is very out of step, because the Iraq war is the first war in American history when the president did not ask for a tax increase to pay for the war. There are only two choices. You can either raise taxes to pay for war, or you can put it on a credit card for our children to pay. There are no other options.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And I think Roosevelt, even though he did in later years run up the deficit, he understood that you had to ask people to sacrifice. And he was a little bitter at the fact that the wealthy were not appreciative of what he had done for them. He had saved them in 1933, saved their fortunes. He compared it -- excuse me -- to a life guard who saves a drowning man in a silk hat, and then four years later the man comes back and says, "hey, where`s my hat?" And by that time, they had become very critical of him and had forgotten that they would have been in the poorhouse if he hadn`t rescued capitalism.}
{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033
\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf2 And you know, a lot of people wanted him to nationalize the banks. The New Dealers, his liberal base, wanted him to have a government takeover of the banks. The fallback position were postal banks. Can you imagine if the post office ran all our banking? Roosevelt said no, I`m going with a conservative approach, the Hoover approach. We`re going to keep banking in private hands. So he was always cutting left and right at the same time. He was not an ideologue. He was a very, very pragmatic president.}
